solutions.content:
This is a relatively easy problem; so let's solve it in more than one way :)

##  Mk I - marking pairs

First we declare a few support variables:
* our string `res`, that will store the result;
* `mustCheck`, a boolean set to `true`  that will take note of changes was we go;
* `len` an int storing the size of the input string `s`, reduced by `- 1`.

We are then going to loop as long as `mustCheck == true`; inside the loop, we will:
* set `mustCheck` to `false`;
* run a for loop with `i` going from `0` to `len` and inside it:
	* set `j` to be initially `i + 1`, then in case it points to a marked character, move it right until you find another non-marked character;
	* check for a match, that you can easily do with `abs(s[i] - s[j]) == 32)`, since all lowercase characters are `32` positions away from their uppercase counterparts; when a match is found:
		* mark both characters as `' '`;
		* move `i` to `j`'s position, so that the next iteration of the for loop will put it to `j + 1`;
		* set `mustCheck` again to `true`, since each new pair found will imply we need to scan again.

Once we have run a full loop without new changes, we can run one last time through `s`, collect all the characters not marked and push them into `res`, before returning it :)

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    string makeGood(string s) {
        // support variables
        string res;
        bool mustCheck = true;
        int len = s.size() - 1;
        // loop to removes pairs
        while (mustCheck) {
            mustCheck = false;
            for (int i = 0, j; i < len; i++) {
                // skipping already marked characters
                if (s[i] == ' ') continue;
                j = i + 1;
                // moving j to the next non marked character
                while (j <= len && s[j] == ' ') j++;
                // checking for a match of upper-+lowercase
                if (abs(s[i] - s[j]) == 32) {
                    s[i] = ' ';
                    s[j] = ' ';
                    i = j -1;
                    mustCheck = true;
                }
            }
        }
        // extracting all "surviving" characters
        for (char c: s) if (c != ' ') res.push_back(c);
        return res;
    }
};
```

## Mk II - marking pairs, improved

Similar to the above, but now when we find a match, we will also "expand" to the characters immediately before and after said match, to avoid finding them later with more expensive new iterations.

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    string makeGood(string s) {
        // support variables
        string res;
        bool mustCheck = true;
        int len = s.size() - 1;
        // loop to removes pairs
        while (mustCheck) {
            mustCheck = false;
            for (int i = 0, j; i < len; i++) {
                // skipping already marked characters
                if (s[i] == ' ') continue;
                j = i + 1;
                // moving j to the next non marked character
                while (j <= len && s[j] == ' ') j++;
                // checking for a match of upper-+lowercase
                while (i >= 0 && j <= len && abs(s[i] - s[j]) == 32) {
                    s[i] = ' ';
                    s[j] = ' ';
                    // checking for more adjacent matches
                    i--, j++;
                    mustCheck = true;
                }
                if (mustCheck) i = j;
            }
        }
        // extracting all "surviving" characters
        for (char c: s) if (c != ' ') res.push_back(c);
        return res;
    }
};
```

## Mk III - using substr

Boring one, this one will also probably use more memory to deal with our substrings as we go.

We will create 2 support variables:
* `res` will store our polished string, initialised to be `s`;
* `len` will store the (constantly updated) length of the string.

Notice that we do not need to use a boolean now - our main loop is turned into a `do... while` and it will check the if at the end of each iteration `res` is different from `s`, which means changes were made and maybe more are needed.

Initially I put the condition as `res != s`, but then I realised that `len != s.size()` is just terribly more efficient: comparing a lot of characters one by one vs. comparing a couple of integers if a big win for larger strings!

Inside the loop, we will proceed similarly to the first method, having a `for` loop go through all the characters (starting from position `1` for convenience) up to `len`; once we find a match, we:
* update `res`, cutting the `2` matching characters from it;
* update `len` to be smaller by `2`;
* shift back `i` by one position, so that it will basically stay at the same place when the loop increments it, to check the new character on that position and potentially save us some loops.

Once we are done and no more changes can be done, we return `res` :)

This approach is significantly less efficient in both time and space than the previous two.

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    string makeGood(string s) {
        // support variables
        string res = s;
        int len = s.size();
        // loop to removes pairs
        do {
            s = res;
            for (int i = 1; i < len; i++) {
                // cutting out matching pairs of characters
                if (abs(res[i - 1] - res[i]) == 32) {
                    // removing the chars from res
                    res = res.substr(0, i - 1) + res.substr(i + 1);
                    // updating len to the new value
                    len -= 2;
                    // moving back i to check the new character in the same position
                    i--;
                }
            }
        } while (len != s.size());
        return res;
    }
};
```

## Mk IV - using substr, improved

Basically a combination of version 3 with the logic of the expanding check from version 2, for the added advantage of doing only one string replacement for potentially multiple matching characters.

Similarly to the other `substr` method, this is still slower and more memory gulping than my first 2 versions.

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    string makeGood(string s) {
        // support variables
        string res = s;
        int len = s.size();
        // loop to removes pairs
        do {
            s = res;
            for (int j = 1, i; j < len; j++) {
                i = j - 1;
                // cutting out matching pairs of characters
                while (i >= 0 && j < len && abs(res[i] - res[j]) == 32) {
                    // updating len to the new value
                    len -= 2;
                    // moving back i to check the new character in the same position
                    i--, j++;
                }
                // removing the matched chars from res
                res = res.substr(0, i + 1) + res.substr(j);
            }
        } while (len != s.size());
        return res;
    }
};
```

## Mk V - using a stack (which is actually a cheaper array)

Similarly to the valid parentheses-family of problems, we store in a "stack" each character, unless it is a match (uppercase/lowercase pair), in which case we pop the last element and move on.

The logic is pretty simple, starting with a few variables:
* `res` is our initially empty response string;
* `st` is going to be our stack (we do not care if it is `char` or `int`, since they work the same for us) - set to be of length equal to `s.size()`, in case we get an input string without a single match;
* `pos` will tell us where to put our next element in the "stack", initialised to `0` (first element).

Looping each character `c` from `s`, we will do 2 simple actions:
* if the "stack" is empty (`pos == 0`) or the character on top of it and the currently parsed one do not match (`abs(st[pos - 1] - c) != 32`), then we add `c` to the stack (`st[pos++] = c`);
* otherwise we just pop from the stack (`pos--`).

Notice that on top of being much more efficient than a normal stack (at possibly the cost of a bit more memory in some cases), this approach also makes easier to extract data from it, since we can just now resize `res` to be `pos` long and write with a normal `for` loops all the characters in it, without having to cause multiple reallocations and/or reverse the string later as you would have to if you composed `res` popping one element at a time from the top of a stack.

If you really wanted to keep things even cheaper, you might have saved declaring `res` and just resized and over-written `s`.

In any case, once you are done you can just return your result string :)

This version seems to be the winner in speed and consumes as much memory as the first one.

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    string makeGood(string s) {
        // support variables
        string res;
        int st[s.size()], pos = 0;
        // loop to removes pairs
        for (char c: s) {
            // adding a char to the stack if the stack is empty
            // or the top does not match the char
            if (!pos || abs(st[pos - 1] - c) != 32) st[pos++] = c;
            else pos--;
        }
        // moving the char out of the stack into res
        if (pos) res.resize(pos);
        for (int i = 0; i < pos; i++) res[i] = st[i];
        return res;
    }
};
```

